#let images = (
  "14-1": (
    caption: [The effect of autonomic nerves on the pacemaker potentials in the SA node. The heart's rhythm is set by the rate of spontaneous depolarization in the SA node. This spontaneous depolarization is known as the *pacemaker potential* (起搏器电位), and its rate is increased by *sympathetic nerve* (交感神经) stimulation and decreased by *parasympathetic nerve* (副交感神经) inhibition.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-1": (
    caption: [Effects of Autonomic Nerve Activity on the Heart, showing the effects of sympathetic and parasympathetic stimulation on the SA node, AV node, and ventricular muscle, including changes in cardiac rate, conduction rate, and contraction strength.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-2": (
    caption: [The Frank-Starling law and sympathetic nerve effects. The graphs demonstrate the *Frank-Starling law* (弗兰克-斯塔林定律): As the *end-diastolic volume* (舒张末期容积) is increased, the *stroke volume* (每搏输出量) is increased. The graphs also demonstrate that the stroke volume is higher at any given end-diastolic volume when the ventricle is stimulated by sympathetic nerves, showing a *positive inotropic effect* (正性肌力作用).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-3": (
    caption: [The Frank-Starling law of the heart. When the heart muscle is subjected to an increasing degree of stretch (a through d), it contracts more forcefully. The contraction strength is indicated on the y-axis as the percent of maximum contraction strength. This demonstrates the relationship between *preload* (前负荷) and contractile force.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-4": (
    caption: [The effect of muscle length and epinephrine on contraction strength. All three curves demonstrate that each muscle contracts with its maximum force at its own optimum length. The decline is steeper for cardiac muscle than for skeletal muscle, demonstrating the importance of the Frank-Starling relationship. *Epinephrine* (肾上腺素) increases the strength of myocardial contraction at any length, demonstrating a positive inotropic effect.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-5": (
    caption: [The regulation of cardiac output. Factors that stimulate *cardiac output* (心输出量) are shown as solid arrows; factors that inhibit cardiac output are shown as dashed arrows. This diagram shows the integration of various regulatory mechanisms including autonomic nervous system, preload, afterload, and venous return.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-6": (
    caption: [The distribution of blood within the circulatory system at rest. The *venous system* (静脉系统) contains most of the blood (60-70%); it functions as a reservoir from which more blood can be added to the circulation under appropriate conditions such as exercise. This demonstrates blood volume distribution across systemic arteries, capillaries, veins, heart, and lungs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-7": (
    caption: [Variables that affect *venous return* (静脉回流) and thus *end-diastolic volume* (舒张末期容积). Direct relationships are indicated by solid arrows; inverse relationships are shown with dashed arrows. Key factors include sympathetic nerve stimulation, skeletal muscle pump, breathing (negative intrathoracic pressure), venous pressure, and venoconstriction.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-8": (
    caption: [The distribution of body water between the *intracellular* (细胞内) and *extracellular* (细胞外) compartments. The extracellular compartment includes the blood plasma and the *interstitial fluid* (组织液). Shows water intake and excretion through kidneys, lungs, skin, and GI tract, with typical volumes for each compartment.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-9": (
    caption: [The distribution of fluid across the walls of a capillary. *Interstitial fluid* (组织液) is formed by filtration (yellow arrows) as a result of blood pressures at the arteriolar ends of capillaries; it is returned to the venular ends of capillaries by the *colloid osmotic pressure* (胶体渗透压) of plasma proteins (orange arrows). This demonstrates *Starling forces* (斯塔林力) and the balance between hydrostatic pressure and oncotic pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-2": (
    caption: [Causes of *Edema* (水肿), including increased blood pressure, increased tissue protein concentration, decreased plasma protein concentration, and obstruction of lymphatic drainage, with examples of conditions that produce each type.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-10": (
    caption: [The severe edema of *elephantiasis* (象皮病). Parasitic larvae that block *lymphatic drainage* (淋巴引流) produce tissue edema and the tremendous enlargement of the limbs and scrotum in elephantiasis.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-11": (
    caption: [The negative feedback control of blood volume and blood osmolality. Thirst and *ADH* (抗利尿激素, antidiuretic hormone) secretion are triggered by a rise in plasma osmolality. Homeostasis is maintained by countermeasures, including drinking and conservation of water by the kidneys.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-12": (
    caption: [The *renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system* (肾素-血管紧张素-醛固酮系统). This system helps to maintain homeostasis through the negative feedback control of blood volume and pressure. Shows the pathway from renin release through angiotensin I and II formation to aldosterone secretion and its effects on blood volume and pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-13": (
    caption: [Negative feedback correction of increased venous return. Stimulation of stretch receptors in the left atrium causes secretion of *atrial natriuretic peptide* (*ANP*, 心房钠尿肽), which increases urinary excretion of salt and water. Simultaneously, decreased *ADH* secretion works together with increased ANP to increase urine volume, lowering blood volume and venous return.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-3": (
    caption: [Estimated Distribution of the Cardiac Output at Rest, showing percentage and volume of blood flow to different organs including liver, kidneys, brain, heart, skeletal muscles, skin, and other organs.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-14": (
    caption: [Blood flow is produced by a pressure difference. The flow of blood in the systemic circulation is ultimately dependent on the pressure difference (ΔP) between the mean pressure of about 100 mmHg at the origin of flow in the aorta and the pressure at the end of the circuit—0 mmHg in the vena cava, where it joins the right atrium.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-15": (
    caption: [The relationships between blood flow, vessel radius, and resistance. (a) The resistance and blood flow are equally divided between two branches of a vessel. (b) A doubling of the radius of one branch and halving of the radius of the other produces a sixteenfold increase in blood flow in the former and a sixteenfold decrease in the latter. This demonstrates *Poiseuille's law* (泊肃叶定律) and the fourth power relationship between radius and flow.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-16": (
    caption: [Blood pressure in different vessels of the systemic circulation. The pressure generated by the beating of the ventricles is largely dissipated by the time the blood gets into the venous system, and this pressure drop occurs primarily as blood goes through the *arterioles* (小动脉) and *capillaries* (毛细血管).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-17": (
    caption: [A diagram of the systemic and pulmonary circulations. With few exceptions (such as blood flow in the renal circulation), the flow of arterial blood is in *parallel* (并联) rather than in *series* (串联)—arterial blood does not usually flow from one organ to another.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-4": (
    caption: [Extrinsic Control of Vascular Resistance and Blood Flow, showing the effects of sympathetic nerve activity and hormones (epinephrine, angiotensin II) on different vascular beds including arterioles in skin, viscera, skeletal muscles, heart, and brain.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-18": (
    caption: [Angiograms of the left coronary artery of a heart patient. These angiograms were taken (a) when the patient's ECG was normal and (b) when the ECG showed evidence of *myocardial ischemia* (心肌缺血), demonstrating coronary artery constriction.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-19": (
    caption: [A diagram of coronary artery bypass surgery. Segments of the *saphenous vein* (隐静脉) of the patient are commonly used as coronary bypass vessels to bypass blocked coronary arteries and restore blood flow to the heart muscle.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-5": (
    caption: [Changes in Skeletal Muscle Blood Flow Under Conditions of Rest and Exercise, showing blood flow (ml/min), percentage of cardiac output, and vascular resistance at rest and during heavy exercise.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-6": (
    caption: [Relationship Between Age and Average Maximum Cardiac Rate, showing how maximum heart rate decreases with age and can be estimated using the formula: Maximum cardiac rate = 220 − age (in years).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-20": (
    caption: [The distribution of blood flow (*cardiac output*, 心输出量) during rest and heavy exercise. At rest, the cardiac output is 5 L per minute; during heavy exercise it increases to 25 L per minute. Blood flow to skeletal muscles increases more than twentyfold because the total cardiac output increases and because the percentage of total flow received by the muscles increases from 15% to 80%.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-7": (
    caption: [Cardiovascular Changes During Moderate Exercise, showing changes in cardiac output, a-v O₂ difference, O₂ uptake, blood flow to muscles and skin, systolic and diastolic blood pressure, and total peripheral resistance.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-21": (
    caption: [Cardiovascular adaptations to exercise. These adaptations (1) increase the cardiac output, and thus the total blood flow; and (2) cause *vasodilation* (血管舒张) in the exercising muscles, thereby diverting a higher proportion of the blood flow to those muscles through redistribution of blood flow.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-22": (
    caption: [Changing patterns of blood flow in the brain. (a) A subject following a moving object with eyes shows high activity over the occipital lobe (*visual cortex*, 视觉皮层). (b) Listening to words activates the temporal lobe (*auditory cortex*, 听觉皮层). (c) Moving fingers activates the contralateral *motor cortex* (运动皮层). (d) Counting to 20 activates the mouth area of motor cortex, supplementary motor area, and auditory cortex. This demonstrates regional cerebral blood flow responding to local metabolic demands.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-23": (
    caption: [Circulation in the skin showing *arteriovenous anastomoses* (动静脉吻合). These vessels function as shunts, allowing blood to be diverted directly from the arteriole to the venule, and thus to bypass superficial capillary loops, playing a crucial role in thermoregulation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-24": (
    caption: [The effect of *vasoconstriction* (血管收缩) on blood pressure. A constriction increases blood pressure upstream (analogous to the arterial pressure) and decreases pressure downstream (analogous to capillary and venous pressure).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-25": (
    caption: [The relationship between blood pressure and the cross-sectional area of vessels. As blood passes from the aorta to the smaller arteries, arterioles, and capillaries, the cross-sectional area increases as the pressure decreases, demonstrating the inverse relationship between vessel cross-sectional area and blood flow velocity.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-26": (
    caption: [The effect of blood pressure on the *baroreceptor* (压力感受器) response. This is a recording of the action potential frequency in sensory nerve fibers from baroreceptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch. As blood pressure increases, the baroreceptors become increasingly stretched, resulting in a higher frequency of action potentials transmitted to the cardiac and vasomotor control centers in the medulla oblongata.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-27": (
    caption: [Structures involved in the *baroreceptor reflex* (压力感受器反射). Sensory stimuli from baroreceptors in the *carotid sinus* (颈动脉窦) and the *aortic arch* (主动脉弓), acting via control centers in the medulla oblongata, affect the activity of sympathetic and parasympathetic nerve fibers in the heart and blood vessels.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-28": (
    caption: [The negative feedback control of blood pressure by the baroreceptor reflex. This reflex helps to maintain an adequate blood pressure upon standing by increasing heart rate, contractility, and vasoconstriction when blood pressure drops, demonstrating *orthostatic* (直立性) blood pressure regulation.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-29": (
    caption: [A pressure cuff and *sphygmomanometer* (血压计) are used to measure blood pressure. The examiner is listening for the *Korotkoff sounds* (柯氏音) using a stethoscope while inflating and deflating the cuff.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-30": (
    caption: [The blood flow and Korotkoff sounds during a blood pressure measurement. When the cuff pressure is above the systolic pressure, the artery is constricted and no blood flows. When the cuff pressure is below the diastolic pressure, blood flow is continuous and silent. Between systolic and diastolic pressures, blood flow is turbulent, producing the characteristic Korotkoff sounds.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-31": (
    caption: [The indirect, or *auscultatory* (听诊) method of blood pressure measurement. The first Korotkoff sound is heard when the cuff pressure is equal to the *systolic blood pressure* (收缩压), and the last sound is heard when the cuff pressure is equal to the *diastolic blood pressure* (舒张压).],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "14-32": (
    caption: [The five phases of blood pressure measurement. Not all phases are heard in all people. The cuff pressure is indicated by the falling dashed black line. Phase I corresponds to systolic pressure, and Phase V (or sometimes Phase IV) corresponds to diastolic pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-8": (
    caption: [Blood Pressure Classification in Adults, showing categories from normal (< 120/80 mmHg) through prehypertension to stages 1 and 2 *hypertension* (高血压), based on systolic and diastolic pressure values.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-9": (
    caption: [Possible Causes of Secondary Hypertension, including renal artery stenosis, glomerulonephritis, pheochromocytoma, Cushing syndrome, and other endocrine and vascular conditions that can cause elevated blood pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-10": (
    caption: [Mechanisms of Action of Selected Antihypertensive Drugs, including diuretics, sympatholytic drugs, vasodilators, ACE inhibitors, and calcium channel blockers, with their specific mechanisms for lowering blood pressure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-11": (
    caption: [Signs of Shock, including rapid heart rate (tachycardia), weak pulse, low blood pressure (hypotension), cold and clammy skin, reduced urine output (oliguria), and metabolic acidosis. These signs indicate inadequate tissue perfusion and circulatory failure.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "table-14-12": (
    caption: [Cardiovascular Reflexes That Help to Compensate for Circulatory Shock, describing baroreceptor reflex, chemoreceptor reflex, and responses involving epinephrine and ADH release, aimed at maintaining blood pressure and tissue perfusion during shock conditions.],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  )
)
